  "prompt": "Are there legal obligations for financial institutions regarding money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, financial institutions have significant legal obligations regarding money laundering prevention. These typically include:\n\n1. Customer Due Diligence (CDD)\n- Verifying customer identities\n- Understanding customer business activities\n- Assessing potential money laundering risks\n\n2. Reporting Requirements\n- Filing Suspicious Activity Reports (SARs)\n- Reporting large cash transactions\n- Maintaining transaction records\n\n3. Know Your Customer (KYC) Procedures\n- Conducting background checks\n- Monitoring customer transactions\n- Identifying potential red flags\n\n4. Compliance with Anti-Money Laundering (AML) Regulations\n- Following national and international standards\n- Implementing internal control systems\n- Training staff on detection methods\n\n5. Risk Assessment\n- Developing risk management strategies\n- Conducting periodic risk evaluations\n- Implementing appropriate monitoring systems\n\n6. Penalties for Non-Compliance\n- Potential significant financial penalties\n- Possible criminal charges\n- Potential loss of operating licenses\n\nThese obligations are designed to prevent financial crimes and help law enforcement track potentially illegal financial activities.\n\nWould you like me to elaborate on any of these specific obligations?",
